00:00:07.210 --> 00:00:10.170
&gt;&gt; Linda Zachrison: Jonas Hassen
Khemiri in his debut novel

00:00:10.170 --> 00:00:17.420
"Ett oga rott," "One Red Eye," hit
the Swedish literary scene in 2003

00:00:17.420 --> 00:00:21.580
and was praised for its comment on
the present and changing society

00:00:21.580 --> 00:00:27.010
with its playful language,
humor, satire, and fast pace.

00:00:27.010 --> 00:00:31.320
Ever since then, Jonas has received
a number of awards for his novels,

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:35.750
for his short stories and
plays in Sweden and abroad.

00:00:35.750 --> 00:00:40.890
He has now written four novels
and six plays and the latest play,

00:00:40.890 --> 00:00:44.630
Everything-- no, the latest novel,
"Everything I Don't Remember,"

00:00:44.630 --> 00:00:48.890
was awarded with the Sweden's
most prestigious literary prize,

00:00:48.890 --> 00:00:54.220
the August Prize, named
after Strindberg, of course.

00:00:54.220 --> 00:00:58.120
Jonas Hassen Khemiri often shifts
perspectives in his writing

00:00:58.120 --> 00:01:01.860
and invites the reader to come
and play with him and his--

00:01:01.860 --> 00:01:06.320
and to play with his
electrified language of his own

00:01:06.320 --> 00:01:09.940
but even got a name for
itself, called Khemirian.

00:01:09.940 --> 00:01:14.560
His work has been translated
into 23 languages

00:01:14.560 --> 00:01:16.280
and his plays have been performed

00:01:16.280 --> 00:01:20.210
by over a hundred companies
around the world.

00:01:20.210 --> 00:01:24.600
Right now, his play, "I
Call My Brothers," is staged

00:01:24.600 --> 00:01:27.860
at the Forum Theatre here
in Washington and it runs

00:01:27.860 --> 00:01:31.140
until October 1st,
so you better hurry.

00:01:31.140 --> 00:01:35.640
A couple of years ago, Jonas wrote
an open letter to the Minister

00:01:35.640 --> 00:01:40.380
of Justice in Sweden who had
publicly defended racial profiling

00:01:40.380 --> 00:01:42.400
in the subways of Stockholm.

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:44.660
It was called "Dear Beatrice."

00:01:44.660 --> 00:01:50.060
It became the most shared piece
in Swedish social media history

00:01:50.060 --> 00:01:53.980
with 250,000 shares
only the first day,

00:01:53.980 --> 00:01:56.530
and it started a Tweeter
movement where people

00:01:56.530 --> 00:02:01.950
under the #dearbeatrice started
sharing their own stories.

00:02:01.950 --> 00:02:06.680
Jonas encourages us all to
look behind the surface,

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:11.570
behind our prejudices,
and behind our fear.

