I tell her about the high energy Wiz
Khalifa concert, hands in the air,

00:31:11.990 --> 00:31:15.460
and their super boring MF
Doom session, yawn attack.

00:31:15.460 --> 00:31:18.120
But I'm not going to
give up, grandma says.

00:31:18.120 --> 00:31:20.560
I'm going to appeal.

00:31:20.560 --> 00:31:23.280
They can't lock me up in here.

00:31:23.280 --> 00:31:27.600
On the last night, we went to
kind of weird Kanye West concert,

00:31:27.600 --> 00:31:29.790
I say, do you know who that is?

00:31:29.790 --> 00:31:34.600
Kanye West, is he Japanese,
grandma answers.

00:31:34.600 --> 00:31:35.900
No, American.

00:31:35.900 --> 00:31:38.200
He had like 20 female
ballet dancers on the stage

00:31:38.200 --> 00:31:42.110
and then extravagant laser show
and fireworks and smoke machines,

00:31:42.110 --> 00:31:44.670
but the only thing that
was good about his show was

00:31:44.670 --> 00:31:48.430
when he accidentally
showed he was human.

00:31:48.430 --> 00:31:51.380
Like when he lost his place
during a memorized interlude

00:31:51.380 --> 00:31:54.990
about how important it
is to follow your dreams.

00:31:54.990 --> 00:31:58.980
All this time, he sneaked a
peek up at his image on one

00:31:58.980 --> 00:32:04.340 position:56%
of the big screens to check
himself out in the middle of a song.

00:32:04.340 --> 00:32:09.340
Then he was transformed from being
a superstar to being a human being.

00:32:09.340 --> 00:32:14.220
But those people aren't
human, grandma says.

00:32:14.220 --> 00:32:19.170
Who? The people who took
my driver's license.

00:32:19.170 --> 00:32:21.940
And every time grandma says
those, she uses that tone

00:32:21.940 --> 00:32:24.040 position:56%
that is impossible to misunderstand.

00:32:24.040 --> 00:32:27.210
Those people, those damn people,
those people that seemed capable

00:32:27.210 --> 00:32:30.800 position:56%
of absolutely anything, those people
who cut pensions without remembering

00:32:30.800 --> 00:32:32.640
who it was who built this country,

00:32:32.640 --> 00:32:35.240
those people who don't have
the slightest idea of how

00:32:35.240 --> 00:32:38.300
to impose order and control
in school classrooms,

00:32:38.300 --> 00:32:41.150
those people who shut down the gas
station in the corner and turned it

00:32:41.150 --> 00:32:43.820
into a graveyard for
rusting ventilation ducts,

00:32:43.820 --> 00:32:48.260
yellow insulation foam,
and broken coffee machines.

00:32:48.260 --> 00:32:51.560
And yet, the worse thing of all
is that those people decided,

00:32:51.560 --> 00:32:55.240
with no warning whatsoever, that
grandma is no longer allowed

00:32:55.240 --> 00:32:59.460
to drive her own gray Mitsubishi,
while she has been driving

00:32:59.460 --> 00:33:04.670
for over 40 years and has never
ever been involved in an accident.

00:33:04.670 --> 00:33:09.050
But there had actually been a few
accidents over the years, I say.

00:33:09.050 --> 00:33:11.920
Yes, of course, says grandma,
a few but not very many

00:33:11.920 --> 00:33:14.010
and none of them were fatal.

00:33:14.010 --> 00:33:15.310
[ Laughter ]

00:33:15.310 --> 00:33:17.490
And that's true.

00:33:17.490 --> 00:33:18.790
Grandma is right.

00:33:18.790 --> 00:33:20.390
She has never been involved
in a fatal accident,

00:33:20.390 --> 00:33:22.180
if you don't count the deer.

00:33:22.180 --> 00:33:24.610
But recently, during
the last few years,

00:33:24.610 --> 00:33:29.010
the number of minor incidents
has increased more and more.

00:33:29.010 --> 00:33:32.130
Like the time grandma picked
up my brother from the airport

00:33:32.130 --> 00:33:36.620
in the countryside and turned out
to the parking lot and then tried

00:33:36.620 --> 00:33:40.350
to drive straight through
a roundabout.

00:33:40.350 --> 00:33:42.060 position:56%
But it was extremely foggy that day.

00:33:42.060 --> 00:33:46.940
Or like the time grandma got a
hole in her fog light after running

00:33:46.940 --> 00:33:49.910
into a carelessly placed broom.

00:33:49.910 --> 00:33:52.300
Or the time grandma was
involved in three crashes

00:33:52.300 --> 00:33:55.320 position:56%
in one year on the Liljeholm Bridge.

00:33:55.320 --> 00:33:58.550
But none of them were
my fault, grandma says.

00:33:58.550 --> 00:34:00.430
And I agree.

00:34:00.430 --> 00:34:05.900
The first time, there was an idiot
who honked at her at a red light.

00:34:05.900 --> 00:34:09.800
And since she had dozed off, she
became frightened and happened

00:34:09.800 --> 00:34:13.240 position:56%
to run into the car in front of her.

00:34:13.240 --> 00:34:15.020
The second time she had
ended up in the wrong lane

00:34:15.020 --> 00:34:17.770
and an idiotic bus driver
refused to let her by.

00:34:17.770 --> 00:34:20.640
And the third crash wasn't
even on the Liljeholm Bridge,

00:34:20.640 --> 00:34:22.940
it was just past it
on the Arsta side.

00:34:22.940 --> 00:34:27.180
A deer was running alongside road
and suddenly without warning,

00:34:27.180 --> 00:34:30.940
the deer swerved to the
left and flung itself

00:34:30.940 --> 00:34:32.990
across the hood of grandma's car.

00:34:32.990 --> 00:34:37.910
Some people, the witnesses,
the insurance company,

00:34:37.910 --> 00:34:42.210
the police report claimed that
grandma ran into the deer.

00:34:42.210 --> 00:34:43.650
She didn't.

00:34:43.650 --> 00:34:47.610
It was the deer that
flung itself onto her car.

00:34:47.610 --> 00:34:49.830
You could almost call
it a suicide attempt,

00:34:49.830 --> 00:34:54.450
grandma says because she could
see that the deer had sad eyes,

00:34:54.450 --> 00:35:01.620
drooping antlers, and a
general air of depression.

00:35:01.620 --> 00:35:03.860
When the-- Before I published
this, I went to grandma's house.

00:35:03.860 --> 00:35:06.180
I sat in front of her and I read
this text because the whole point

00:35:06.180 --> 00:35:08.360
of this text is to
get her to understand

00:35:08.360 --> 00:35:11.200
that she has to let us help us.

00:35:11.200 --> 00:35:13.160
Like she has done everything
throughout her life,

00:35:13.160 --> 00:35:15.990
she's always helped us,
but she can't ask for help.

00:35:15.990 --> 00:35:20.680
So the whole point of this text is
just you have to let us help you.

00:35:20.680 --> 00:35:24.000
As I'm reading this, I'm thinking
that she's going to interrupt me

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:26.590
and say something like, come on,

00:35:26.590 --> 00:35:28.510
that's a little bit
over the top, you know.

00:35:28.510 --> 00:35:30.860
That's like your first
novel, kind of.

00:35:30.860 --> 00:35:32.860
But she stopped me after-- I
was reading about the deer,

00:35:32.860 --> 00:35:34.760
she stopped me and she
put her hand at me,

00:35:34.760 --> 00:35:37.470
her hand on mine and
she said, "Jonas."

00:35:37.470 --> 00:35:39.760
I was like, "Yeah?"

00:35:39.760 --> 00:35:42.010
"That's the best thing
you've ever written."

00:35:42.010 --> 00:35:43.310
[ Laughter ]

00:35:43.310 --> 00:35:46.540
It was exactly like that.

00:35:46.540 --> 00:35:49.190
And it was.

00:35:49.190 --> 00:35:54.140
Like in her memory of that
incident, it was exactly like that.

00:35:54.140 --> 00:35:57.920
Because if it had been any
other way, she would be forced

00:35:57.920 --> 00:36:03.040
to change her idea of who she was
and then things would get tricky.

00:36:03.040 --> 00:36:07.750
When the coffee is gone, we say
goodbye and I hide the car keys

00:36:07.750 --> 00:36:12.230
where she can't find them
way up high on the hat rack.

00:36:12.230 --> 00:36:15.230
Later that afternoon, she calls
and asks when I'm going to come

00:36:15.230 --> 00:36:19.450
by with the car or whether I
had fun at the music festival.

00:36:19.450 --> 00:36:21.200
She calls again that
evening and asks

00:36:21.200 --> 00:36:23.120
if I'm coming by with the car soon.

00:36:23.120 --> 00:36:25.570
We can drink coffee,
we can eat cookies.

00:36:25.570 --> 00:36:29.200 position:56%
I'm curious to hear what it was
like at that festival in Gothenburg.

00:36:29.200 --> 00:36:33.640
The next day, she calls at dawn
and asks when I'm going to pick her

00:36:33.640 --> 00:36:36.670
up so we can drive up to Stockholm.

00:36:36.670 --> 00:36:38.420
She doesn't want to be
in the country anymore.

00:36:38.420 --> 00:36:39.720
She wants to go home.

00:36:39.720 --> 00:36:41.820
She feels isolated.

00:36:41.820 --> 00:36:46.410
But grandma, I say, you're
already in Stockholm.

00:36:46.410 --> 00:36:47.820
You are home.

00:36:47.820 --> 00:36:49.120
Can't you tell?

00:36:49.120 --> 00:36:51.330
You're calling me from
your regular home number.

00:36:51.330 --> 00:36:53.030
You're lying in your
regular old bed.

00:36:53.030 --> 00:36:55.120
And if you just look
a little to the right,

00:36:55.120 --> 00:36:59.900 position:56%
you can see a regular old night
stand, with the old Vademecum bottle

00:36:59.900 --> 00:37:02.810
and a glass of water
and the tattered Bible

00:37:02.810 --> 00:37:05.910
and the blinking clock radio.

00:37:05.910 --> 00:37:11.540
And right next to the bed is the
note you've written to yourself.

00:37:11.540 --> 00:37:19.730
Your beautiful, ornate handwriting
that says, "I am in Stockholm.

00:37:19.730 --> 00:37:21.600
I'm not going anywhere."

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:28.200
And grandma finds the note and
reads the words and says, "Oh,

00:37:28.200 --> 00:37:31.010
I guess I'm starting
to get a bit nutty."

00:37:31.010 --> 00:37:34.500
And we hung up and I persuade
myself that my memories are eternal

00:37:34.500 --> 00:37:37.080
and I will never need
to write something

00:37:37.080 --> 00:37:39.900
down for it to remain with me.

00:37:41.660 --> 00:37:45.050
My phone is quiet for 10
minutes before it rings again

00:37:45.050 --> 00:37:47.350
and it's grandma wanting
to know when I'm coming

00:37:47.350 --> 00:37:49.990
by to drop off the car and how
it went at that music festival

00:37:49.990 --> 00:37:55.080
in Gothenburg and I say the
music festival was totally wicked

00:37:55.080 --> 00:37:59.420
and magical and I'm so glad
you decided to come along.

00:37:59.420 --> 00:38:03.510
It was so fun to see you rocking
out to Prince hits and clapping

00:38:03.510 --> 00:38:05.520
in time with Wiz Khalifa.

00:38:05.520 --> 00:38:08.960
And I'm sure you remember, you
remember, right, how the audience

00:38:08.960 --> 00:38:13.000
in that church cheered when
you climbed up on stage

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:19.590
to sing the second verse of
James Blake's encore song, right?

00:38:19.590 --> 00:38:25.130
And grandma is quiet for a few
seconds and then she says, "Oh,

00:38:25.130 --> 00:38:27.980
now you're just making things up."

00:38:27.980 --> 00:38:32.070
But you can hear that
she is smiling.

00:38:32.070 --> 00:38:34.390
Thank you very much for coming
and if there are any questions,

00:38:34.390 --> 00:38:36.510
I'd be happy to answer them.

00:38:36.510 --> 00:38:47.510
[ Applause ]

00:38:47.510 --> 00:38:51.620
So I'm being told by a sign
that we have five minutes,

00:38:51.620 --> 00:38:54.210
if there are any questions or--

00:38:54.210 --> 00:38:56.820
&gt;&gt; I wanted to say that I
love what you say about memory

00:38:56.820 --> 00:38:58.140
and when we're losing our memory.

00:38:58.140 --> 00:39:01.150
I watched my mother go through
that and I just think that the--

00:39:01.150 --> 00:39:05.140
all the different ways you looked
at it and the ways that you looked

00:39:05.140 --> 00:39:07.080
at what makes up a human being

00:39:07.080 --> 00:39:09.220
from all the perspectives
is just very moving.

00:39:09.220 --> 00:39:10.520
Thank you very much.

00:39:10.520 --> 00:39:11.820
&gt;&gt; Jonas Hassen Khemiri:
Thank you very much.

00:39:11.820 --> 00:39:13.620
I'm really happy to hear that.

00:39:13.620 --> 00:39:16.330
[ Applause ]

00:39:16.330 --> 00:39:17.630
Yes.

00:39:17.630 --> 00:39:21.020
&gt;&gt; I was intrigued by what you
said about returning to Stockholm

00:39:21.020 --> 00:39:23.470
and the emphasis on the economy.

00:39:23.470 --> 00:39:28.720 position:56%
And I was wondering how you've seen
economic issues impact not only your

00:39:28.720 --> 00:39:31.940
own work but the work of
other Swedish novelists

00:39:31.940 --> 00:39:33.240
who are your contemporaries

00:39:33.240 --> 00:39:38.070
and why you think those might
be surprising as a theme.

00:39:38.070 --> 00:39:40.300
&gt;&gt; Jonas Hassen Khemiri: I
think-- that's a great question.

00:39:40.300 --> 00:39:48.370
I think maybe I had-- I was more--
I was quite-- how should I put it.

00:39:48.370 --> 00:39:50.640
I'm a failed economist.

00:39:50.640 --> 00:39:56.010
Like I have studied economy when
I was young and I never graduated

00:39:56.010 --> 00:40:00.040
which my father reminds
me about every 10 minutes.

00:40:00.040 --> 00:40:03.420
But I've always been
fascinated with the kind

00:40:03.420 --> 00:40:06.590
of the power that money
can give you.

00:40:06.590 --> 00:40:08.800
And I think the money-- the power

00:40:08.800 --> 00:40:11.850
and the privilege that
money can give you.

00:40:11.850 --> 00:40:15.260
So, since I became a father,
I had this kind of theme.

00:40:15.260 --> 00:40:18.990
My latest play was called "Almost
Equal To" and that also deals

00:40:18.990 --> 00:40:25.400
with economy and kind of
the challenges of knowing

00:40:25.400 --> 00:40:30.620
that there's a system that has
all these negative consequences,

00:40:30.620 --> 00:40:34.940
but not really knowing how
to formulate an alternative.

00:40:34.940 --> 00:40:38.900 position:56%
And I think that I-- before I became
a father, I think I had this idea

00:40:38.900 --> 00:40:47.320
that I could be free to create
in my fictional universe.

00:40:47.320 --> 00:40:51.450
But I think becoming a father,
to think I realize that my idea

00:40:51.450 --> 00:40:54.890
of economics were quite-- was
quite simplified actually,

00:40:54.890 --> 00:41:02.170 position:56%
that it was very tricky to create
this kind of separate universe from,

00:41:02.170 --> 00:41:04.950
yeah, the everyday
reality in Stockholm.

00:41:04.950 --> 00:41:10.660
And like the main shift that has
happened in Stockholm is that we--

00:41:10.660 --> 00:41:14.630
the latest 10 and 20 years, we've
changed the whole housing market.

00:41:14.630 --> 00:41:19.200 position:56%
So, we've gone from a rent-based
system to now we can actually invest

00:41:19.200 --> 00:41:22.550
in housing which creates all this--

00:41:22.550 --> 00:41:25.030
all kinds of interesting
consequences,

00:41:25.030 --> 00:41:29.210
not only for the people who-- like
I had the luxury of being able

00:41:29.210 --> 00:41:32.450
to find a secure place
for my family.

00:41:32.450 --> 00:41:34.440
But it was also interesting
to see how

00:41:34.440 --> 00:41:37.350 position:56%
that changed my view of my own city.

00:41:37.350 --> 00:41:39.900
Because if you had the
illusion that you can own a part

00:41:39.900 --> 00:41:44.600
of a physical space, the people
who don't have that ability,

00:41:44.600 --> 00:41:51.260
you start seeing them as with
a suspicion that I was, yeah,

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:57.000
that I didn't think that I was
capable with that, kind of.

00:41:57.000 --> 00:41:58.300
Yeah.

00:41:58.300 --> 00:42:00.340
&gt;&gt; Oh, you want to go first?

00:42:00.340 --> 00:42:01.640
&gt;&gt; Jonas Hassen Khemiri: Yeah.

00:42:01.640 --> 00:42:02.940
&gt;&gt; Oh, OK.

00:42:02.940 --> 00:42:06.140
My question is how long did
it take you to write the book

00:42:06.140 --> 00:42:11.120
and how do you find the
strength to write again

00:42:11.120 --> 00:42:13.910
when your friend dies
and you feel empty?

00:42:13.910 --> 00:42:17.690 position:56%
How do you move on and keep writing?

00:42:17.690 --> 00:42:19.030
Do you stop?

00:42:19.030 --> 00:42:25.900
How do you, I guess, get to
starting and completing a book?

00:42:25.900 --> 00:42:29.560
&gt;&gt; Jonas Hassen Khemiri:
Well, this one was trickier

00:42:29.560 --> 00:42:30.980
than the other ones, actually.

00:42:30.980 --> 00:42:35.500
And I think it had to do
with that feeling that I've--

00:42:35.500 --> 00:42:36.800
so I've been writing all my life.

00:42:36.800 --> 00:42:39.780
That has been my main joy, like
the best drug I know is to--

00:42:39.780 --> 00:42:43.350
just to go home and
to write and to--

00:42:43.350 --> 00:42:47.120
I've never doubted
the value of words.

00:42:47.120 --> 00:42:50.690 position:56%
But having that loss in my life, for
the first time, it was as if I kind

00:42:50.690 --> 00:42:55.090
of doubted what words
could do actually.

00:42:55.090 --> 00:43:06.430 position:56%
And I don't think I have a-- the one
thing that got me out of that whole

00:43:06.430 --> 00:43:12.780
of feeling like doubting what
words could do was just to realize

00:43:12.780 --> 00:43:17.700
that even though they
couldn't, how should I put it,

00:43:17.700 --> 00:43:22.590
even though they couldn't
recreate the person who was gone,

00:43:22.590 --> 00:43:26.660
the feelings that I had of having
lost her were able to capture--

00:43:26.660 --> 00:43:29.880
I was able to put that on the
page, and there were many things

00:43:29.880 --> 00:43:32.100
that happened after having lost her

00:43:32.100 --> 00:43:38.690
that I thought would be
tricky to put in post.

00:43:38.690 --> 00:43:42.360
One thing that was weird to me that
we all know if we lose someone,

00:43:42.360 --> 00:43:45.070
that person is gone, but
the strange thing was

00:43:45.070 --> 00:43:48.070
that even though she was gone,
she was present everywhere.

00:43:48.070 --> 00:43:51.050
So I kept seeing her everywhere,
I kept just speaking my memories

00:43:51.050 --> 00:43:52.920
like the amounts of
memories that kept coming

00:43:52.920 --> 00:43:57.000
up that we had shared
was just endless.

00:43:57.000 --> 00:44:03.060
So, the only way I had-- the only
way I could deal with that was

00:44:03.060 --> 00:44:08.330
to try to write myself
out of it and, yeah.

00:44:08.330 --> 00:44:10.750
In the end, it became
this book, but--

00:44:10.750 --> 00:44:12.670
&gt;&gt; OK.

00:44:12.670 --> 00:44:14.970
&gt;&gt; Jonas Hassen Khemiri: Now, I'm
seeing a sign that says wrap up

00:44:14.970 --> 00:44:18.010
and I'm guessing that that
